Traditional CSS (using Flexbox):
html
<div class="parent">
  <div class="child">Centered Content</div>
</div>

css
.parent {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: center;
  align-items: center;
  height: 100vh;
}
.child {
  /* No additional centering needed */
}

Tailwind CSS:
html
<div class="h-screen flex items-center justify-center">
  <div>Centered Content</div>
</div>

In Tailwind, `h-screen` sets the height, `flex` enables flexbox, `items-center` centers vertically, and `justify-center` centers horizontally—all in a single, predictable class set.

Here’s a CSS rule that creates a new stacking context:
css
.sticky-header {
  position: sticky;
  top: 0;
  z-index: 10;
  background: white;
}

A new stacking context is necessary when you need to ensure that an element (like a sticky header) appears above other content consistently, regardless of the document’s scroll position. The `z-index` property will only work within the same stacking context, so creating one ensures the header remains visible. Other properties like `opacity`, `transform`, or `filter` can also create stacking contexts.
